******
[1] Idaho
Date: Thu 22 Jul 2010
Source: Oregon Public Broadcasting [edited]
<http://news.opb.org/article/9519-north-idaho-suffers-through-whooping-cough-outbreak/>


Whooping cough is hitting Idaho hard. 77 cases of pertussis have been
reported, about twice the average. Cynthia Taggart from the Panhandle
Health District says there's no particular reason for the outbreak.
She says the illness tends to go in cycles. She says the best way to
prevent the disease is through immunization.

Children get a series of shots through infancy. But Taggart says kids
become more vulnerable as they age.

Cynthia Taggart: "Kids 11 and 12 need their booster. They need to be
revaccinated, even kids who have been vaccinated for pertussis. But
it wears off over time. And, you know, a lot of parents aren't aware
of that." Health officials like Taggart also encourage adults who
have contact with children to get a special pertussis booster.

[Byline: Doug Nadvornick]

