******
[3] California
Date: Fri 23 Jul 2010
Source: Associated Press [edited]
<http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504763_162-20011458-10391704.html>


The state recorded about 1500 cases through 13 Jul 2010, a 5-fold
increase over the same period in 2009. Six infants have died in the
recent outbreak. Yesterday, 22 Jul 2010, officials in Calaveras
County near Sacramento announced 3 new cases of the sometimes-deadly
illness.

Whooping cough (also known as pertussis) is a highly contagious
bacterial infection that attacks the respiratory system. The
infection is preventable by vaccination, which is why Calaveras
County Health Officer Dr. Dean Kelaita urged people, especially
expectant mothers and those with infants in their households, to get
immunized, according to the Record Net newspaper.

Still, 5 of the 6 infants who died in California were under 3 months
old, which is too young for immunization.

